text:
dear white women, we need to be better.

it's not enough to talk about intersectionality in our safe spaces. it's not enough to post about ourselves or our mothers or grandmothers marching for civil rights. 
because what we are doing when we leave those spaces is contradictory.

i'm talking to the white women like the lady who stood in the doorway of an apartment building blocking a black man from entering because she "felt unsafe" - who proceeded to call the police on a man who lived in said building.

i'm talking to the white women like the woman who started a business with a racist slur in the name - who when she was informed that that word was a slur, proceeded to make a live video crying about how she didn't know it was a slur, and apologizing to her customers, but ultimately saying that since she didn't know that word was a slur it is okay for her to use it. 
i'm talking to the white women who hear about sexual assault and rape cases, who proceed to make jokes on social media about it, or to talk about how not all men commit sexual assault.

i'm talking to the white women who successfully protest pipelines going near their homes, but don't support indigenous people doing the exact same thing because "well, we need oil!"
i'm talking to the white women who proudly talk about their history supporting civil rights (marching with dr. king!) but still give stink-eye to the woc spending their ebt next to them at the grocery store.

i'm talking to the white women who "prefer to stay out of politics" and "just want to think about positive things" - that's white privilege and you are taking advantage of it.

i'm talking to the white women who see posts about not wearing cultures as costumes at halloween, but dress their daughters up as pocahontas anyway because "she really wants to and i don't want to talk about all that stuff with her yet, she's a child!!" you. are. part. of. the. problem. 
this is not being allies. 
the correct response to being told you are using a racial slur is to apologize to the person hurt by that word, and to immediately stop using that word. don't center yourself. it's not about you.
(cont. in comment)

text: in the era of #metoo josie rourke has reimagined #shakespeare #measureformeasure that questions whether men and women that do the same thing are judged differently. the play opens with @j_a_lowden assuming delegated authority from the duke and charging claudio with the draconian offence of fornication out of wedlock. @wellhayley plays claudioâ€™s sister isabella who has to decide whether to give up her life in order to save her brother. #hayleyatwell gives a beautifully controlled performance as the defiantly chaste novice whilst #jacklowden with his soft scottish burr is captivating as the tyrannical purist. this is the traditional interpretation of the play as an abuse of power by politicians. however with a flash of light we are suddenly transported to a modern day court complete with text messages and selfies. now, the roles have been reversed and the play repeated but this time with a male novice and a female deputy. rourke has opted to dispense with the religiosity of the original text for a secular interpretation with angelo as a reformed addict (and seemingly chaste as part of some unexplained cult). ultimately the message is that power corrupts irrespective of gender. it is an ingenious concept executed with aplomb even if purists may find that too much of the plot, humour and exacting arguments have been jettisoned to accommodate the retelling. the supporting cast are uniformly excellent with special mention to a scene-stealing performance from @jackie_clune as a russian pompey in the second act. the minimalistic set enables a swift transition between scenes and peter mckintosh again proves adept at designing for the small @donmarwarehouse stage. this is rourkeâ€™s penultimate production at #donmarwarehouse and i canâ€™t wait to see her final show. #theatre #theater #theatregeek #westend #broadway #setdesign #lightingdesign #drama #theatrelife #london #theatrearts #theatreland #coventgarden #londontheatrereviews

text:
nuestra amiga lorena, @aguilore__ nos envÃ­o el siguiente comentario: "la mujer que fui" es un libro que vale la pena leer  porque a travÃ©s de la historia de elizabeth, la protagonista, reconocemos en nosotras los efectos que ha dejado la cultura machista y patriarcal.
aunque el libro trata de violencia intrafamiliar, tambiÃ©n nos remite a la violencia presente en la educaciÃ³n que recibimos y que nos lleva a sentir culpa cuando no vivimos para hacer felices a los demÃ¡s y a la sensaciÃ³n de no merecer nada gratuitamente.

text:
i wrote this exactly a year ago. and it is still relevant today: 
i want to be treated like a person.

i want to be able to reach out to a cool guy i can see myself being friends with without them immediately thinking something romantic or sexual. i want them to respect me and still be able to hang with me when i say i am looking for friendship. 
i don't want to be doubted in my abilities. i want to bring ideas to the table and have them taken seriously. i don't want to be interrupted. i don't want to be talked over or looked over. i don't want to be called a bitch when i stand up for myself or when i'm direct when i speak.

i want to be seen as someone with value for my brain. i don't want to be constantly judged for my appearances, because i have so much more to offer than that.

don't fucking tell me that i need to have children right away. that a man has to be the provider in a family. that everything revolves around the male in my life. that i am not enough as a woman with dreams and goals, whether a man be in my life or not. 
see me for me.

#metoo #femenist #femalepower #thefutureisfemale #selflove #stepupmen

text:
another thing that's been so helpful to me in my own journey of healing from childhood sexual assault and incest has been to claim my shadow.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
our shadow is all those parts of ourselves that we've been taught weren't acceptable. had to be hidden.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
they become the parts of our souls -- our psyches -- that we're afraid of.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
but guess what? we can't pretend away reality. not possible.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
and a lot of what we're afraid of is our own power. our brilliance. our beauty. our much-ness. our big-ness.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
"the message we get from this hidden place is simple: there is something wrong with me. i'm not okay. i'm not lovable. i'm not deserving. i'm not worthy." ("the dark side of the light chasers," by debbie ford)â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
when we live and work and love from a place of believing something's wrong with us, that we're square pegs/round holes, when we are not enough ... that is exactly what we'll get back.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

text:
in 1926, three rooms with connecting tunnels within and underneath the great sphinx of giza were violated, condemned with concrete and sealed shut. there are photographs of work men inside these rooms & underground passage-ways, just ask egyptian director of antiquities zahi hawass. roman royalty would rent ($$$) these sphinx rooms to nobility 365 nights a year because it was believed that these rooms would bestow anyone who slept inside them with prophetic dreams. by marketing the sphinx rooms as dream incubators at great cost, so they thought, the roman elite could benefit greatly by keeping secret the knowledge of the great sphinxâ€™s underground â€œromanâ€ hotel. ğŸ”ºğŸ›¸ğŸŒŠ
as a child, i was baptized by mormons and placed into the boy scouts of america program. not only was i violently raped and routinely molested, but forced to witness other boys being raped as well by sadistic, respected mormon authorities. i had great trouble sleeping as a kid...trauma is very tricky.. after loosing my friend chris allegedly to suicide at a young age, and being unable to reconcile an innocent soul cast into eternal darkness, i sought expression & picked up my older brothers guitar. my father gave me my first lesson, to help in grieving chris who was a guitar player (he supposedly hanged himself in the closet with an instrument cable). i started randomly dreaming about the giza pyramids & the great sphinx with a crown of thorns placed upon its head(for all u freudians out there: freemason inspired mormon doctrine+disneyâ€™s â€œaladdinâ€ cia magic carpet ride program?), and eventually sank into a very dark and lonesome sub-conscious rabbit hole goose chase to finally confront this golden egg like forgotten shadow trauma demon -twenty years later. ğŸ¦‹
but now we are awake. 
all is not in everything 
but it is all-important to keep awake.
also, we have been working on a new single that i am violently proud ofğŸ”¥

text:
itâ€™s hard being the worst one in the class but youâ€™ll only get better by trying.
.
i was <am> terrible at math. i would breakout in hives if i had to solve a problem on the board. i relied on the free answers in the back of the book for homework assignments (you youngins donâ€™t know what iâ€™m talking about but my 30s ladies remember!). it just didnâ€™t come naturally to me at all. i could tell by the pace my classmates worked at that i was definitely missing something. so you know what i did?
.
i stayed after school for tutoring in high school even though i really didnâ€™t like the teacher. i did homework that wasnâ€™t required. i did every extra credit assignment. i tried my absolute hardest in every one of those classes. i easily couldâ€™ve thrown in the towel and said screw it i donâ€™t like it, iâ€™m not any good at it, iâ€™m embarrassed to do it in front of my peers, iâ€™m not gonna pursue a field in math, etc. but no. i busted my butt and graduated in the top 10 of my class.
.
how could the trajectory of my life changed if i hadnâ€™t kept trying? my gpa wouldâ€™ve suffered, my college options wouldâ€™ve been more limited, i wouldâ€™ve built a precedent that just because itâ€™s hard you quit.
.
we are all the â€œworstâ€ at some time but we will never get better if we donâ€™t try. so what if you have to work twice as hard at __________?? we do what we have to do with blinders on and focus only on our goal. not where everyone else is.
.
hereâ€™s to being the best â€œworstâ€ we can be this week and refusing to give up.ğŸ’™

text:
â€œin recent years, a new wave of state and local activity has transformed minimum wage policy in the u.s. as of august 2018, ten large cities and seven states have enacted minimum wage policies in the $12 to $15 range. dozens of smaller cities and counties have also enacted wage standards in this range. these higher minimum wages, which are being phased in gradually, will cover well over 20 percent of the u.s. workforce. with a substantial number of additional cities and states poised to soon enact similar policies, a large portion of the u.s. labor market will be held to a higher wage standard than has been typical over the past 50 years.

these minimum wage levels substantially exceed the previous peak in the federal minimum wage, which reached just under $10 (in todayâ€™s dollars) in the late 1960s. as a result, the new policies will increase pay directly for 15 to 30 percent of the workforce in these cities and as much as 40 to 50 percent of the workforce in some industries and regions. by contrast, the federal and state minimum wage increases between 1984 and 2014 increased pay directly for less than eight percent of the applicable workforce.

this report examines the effects of these new policies. although minimum wage effects on employment have been much studied and debated, this new wave of higher minimum wages attains levels beyond the evidential reach of most previous studies. moreover, city-level policies might have effects that differ from those of state and federal policies. yet, most of the empirical studies of minimum wages focus on the state and federal-level policies. the literature on the effects of city-level minimum wages is much smaller. our report helps fill these gaps.â€
.
.
.

my apologies for the lack of posts the past few days, i have been reeling from an experience with sexual harassment i dealt with and the subsequent fall out. being a sexual assault survivor three times over, i am hypersensitive to the pervasive and systemic rape culture that defines our society. and i refuse to put up with it... sometimes that means i get into uncomfortable conversations with (mostly) men who are incapable of being confronted. âœ¨
â€¢
you can read all about it in my latest blog post (link in bio), but what has struck the biggest cord with me are the reactions to my speaking out. âœ¨
â€¢
overall, most of my interactions have been overwhelmingly positive with people from different circles taking the time to message me their words of support or to share their own experiences with sexual harassment, many of which society turned a blind eye to. âœ¨
â€¢
but there have also been the expected responses (which, sadly not shockingly, have only been from men) coming forward to question my speaking out. to attempt to shame me into silence. to plead for consideration of the assailantâ€™s future/feelings/reputation. and iâ€™ve had enough of it. âœ¨
â€¢
every time someone defends an assailant, be it for sexual harassment, sexual assault, or anywhere in between, they are negating the trauma and  devastating changes the victim faced, faces, and will continue to face for the coming years. âœ¨
â€¢
someone who chooses to violate, harass, or harm another human being does not deserve anonymity. they are not owed sympathy for all they stand to lose as a result of their choices. they are not the victims in these scenarios. ever. âœ¨
â€¢
iâ€™m sad. iâ€™m enraged. iâ€™m scared. i feel hopeless. i feel a myriad of emotions because of how broken our world is. how this is a socially acceptable response. how iâ€™m an outlier for taking a stand and saying enough. i feel all of these things, but i will never stop raising my voice for the voiceless. âœŠğŸ»âœ¨
â€¢
if you or someone you know is struggling as the result of sexual harassment or abuse please reach out. if you donâ€™t know where to go, message me. âœ¨ #metoo

text:
first things first. this is going to be completely your choice. i can't tell you what to do and you wouldn't want me to anyway. that being said setting boundaries in your life is going to be one of the most important thing you do. if you allow abusers to be in your life that have never taken responsibility then the end result will not be good. but i will help you break it down so you can decide for yourself. 
1. has this person taken full responsibility for what they did to you and they 100% acknowledge that it was wrong? or is it not talked about, addressed, or acknowledged?

2. if they haven't taken responsibility for what they did then ask yourself.. why do you want them in your life? because they are family and you don't want to cause problems? because you are afraid that you will lose them? if that's the case then ask yourself, do i really want someone in my life that has violated me, abused me, disrespected me, hasn't taken responsibility, continues to disrespect me, and acts like there's no issue?

3. how does it truly make you feel to be around this person? if it causes you any anxiety, uneasiness, or triggering feelings then there's your answer. allowing someone into your life that you feel this way around isn't worth the stress. you have every right to be selective with who you allow into your life especially if they have abused you in the past. protect your energy, your happiness, and your boundaries. just because they are "family" doesn't allow them to have a presence in your life. family is who you choose to call familyâ¤ï¸

text:
it's been a year since the beginning of the online #metoo movement. we have come far. the silence has been broken and our lived experiences are finally being heard. however, there is still so much more work to be done. we have acknowledged that there is a problem but now we need to implement solutions. without fixing the problem it just becomes a viral hashtag. this movement is so powerful. we have spoken but we haven't yet been assured that we have been listened too. we need change now. educational change, societal change, policy change, and judicial change. there's a wealth of information now to inform that change. it's time we saw it materialise. 
thank you to tarana burke who orchestrated this entire movement as well as alyssa milano who helped spread the word and all the other wonderful people who used their platform to speak out. #metoo #metoomovement #timesup #thegeminiproject #consent #endrapeculture #stopvictimblaming #change #wedemandjustice #believesurvivors #whyididntreport #survivorculture
